{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181019041005|864738439","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Joe_Kennedy_III","to":"Joe Kennedy III"}],"pages":{"34500244":{"pageid":34500244,"ns":0,"title":"Joe Kennedy III","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-23T05:22:22Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{short description|U.S. Representative from Massachusetts}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{GA icon}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Joe Kennedy III\n|image       = Joe Kennedy III, 115th official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Massachusetts]]\n|district    = {{ushr|MA|4|4th}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Barney Frank]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Joseph Patrick Kennedy III\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1980|10|4}}\n|birth_place = [[Boston]], Massachusetts, U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = {{marriage|Lauren Birchfield|December 1, 2012}}\n|children    = 2\n|parents     = [[Joseph P. Kennedy II]] (Father) \nSheila Brewster Rauch (Mother)\n|relatives   = ''See [[Kennedy family]]''\n|education   = [[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|kennedy.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Joseph Patrick Kennedy III''' (born October 4, 1980), is an American lawyer and politician serving as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|MA|4}} since 2013. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], his congressional district extends from the western suburbs of [[Boston]] to the state's [[South Coast (Massachusetts)|South Coast]]. A son of former Representative [[Joseph P. Kennedy II]], he worked as a [[Peace Corps]] volunteer and as an assistant district attorney in the [[Cape and Islands]] and [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts]] offices before his election to Congress.\n\nKennedy is a grandson of [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] and former [[United States Attorney General]] [[Robert F. Kennedy|Robert F. \"Bobby\" Kennedy]], a grand-nephew of President [[John F. Kennedy]] and U.S. Senator [[Ted Kennedy]], and a great-grandson of [[Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.|Joseph Patrick Kennedy]], former [[United States Ambassador to the United Kingdom|U.S. Ambassador to the United Kingdom]]. His great-grandmother [[Rose Kennedy]] was the daughter of [[John F. Fitzgerald]], a member of the U.S. House of Representatives and Mayor of Boston.\n\nBorn in [[Brighton, Massachusetts]], Kennedy was raised in the Boston area with his twin brother, Matthew Rauch \"Matt\" Kennedy. After graduating from [[Stanford University]] he spent two years in the [[Dominican Republic]] as a member of the Peace Corps, and earned his law degree at [[Harvard Law School]] in 2009. He resigned as a prosecutor in early 2012 to run for the seat held by retiring Congressman [[Barney Frank]]. He was sworn into office in January 2013 and sits on the [[U.S. House Committee on Energy and Commerce]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nKennedy was born October 4, 1980<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=K000379 |title=Kennedy, Joseph P. III |work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress}}</ref> in [[Brighton, Boston|Brighton]], a neighborhood of [[Boston]], to Sheila Brewster (Rauch) and [[Joseph P. Kennedy II|Joseph Patrick \"Joe\" Kennedy II]]. He was born eight minutes after his fraternal twin brother, Matthew. He and Matt are the eldest grandsons of Senator [[Robert F. Kennedy|Robert Francis \"Bobby\" Kennedy]] and [[Ethel Kennedy|Ethel Skakel]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/16/magazine/joe-kennedy-iii.html?pagewanted=all | title = Keeping Up With the Kennedys | author = Edith Zimmerman | work = [[The New York Times]] | date=September 12, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"globe-2012\">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2012/03/18/for_the_kennedy_clan_he_is_generation_next/|work=[[The Boston Globe]] |title=For the Kennedy clan, he is Generation Next |date=March 17, 2012 |author=Jacobs, Sally}}</ref> Kennedy was raised in Brighton and in the coastal town of [[Marshfield, Massachusetts|Marshfield]], also spending summers on [[Cape Cod]].<ref name=\"capecod-2010\">{{cite news|url=http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100228/NEWS/2280329/-1/news |title=Not your average Joe (Kennedy) |work=[[Cape Cod Times]] |date=February 28, 2010 |author=Vosk, Stephanie |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512064256/http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20100228%2FNEWS%2F2280329%2F-1%2Fnews |archivedate=May 12, 2013 |df= }}</ref> From birth, Kennedy was engulfed in politics; in 1980, his parents were working on the [[Democratic Party presidential primaries, 1980|presidential campaign]] of U.S. Senator [[Ted Kennedy]], the boys' great-uncle. Kennedy's father was elected to Congress in 1986. The pressures of political life strained Joseph and Sheila's marriage, and they divorced in 1991. The twins spent the following years moving between Brighton and Cambridge.<ref name=\"globe-2012\" />\n\n[[File:Joseph P Kennedy III in Dominican Republic.png|thumb|left|Kennedy (left) in the Dominican Republic as part of the Peace Corps]]\nAfter graduating from the [[Buckingham Browne & Nichols]] School in Cambridge, Kennedy along with his brother enrolled in [[Stanford University]], where he majored in [[management science]] and engineering.  Kennedy's reputation as a [[teetotaler]] earned him the college nickname \"Milkman\", as his teammates on the club [[lacrosse]] team would jokingly order him glasses of milk at bars.<ref name=\"globe-2012\" /><ref name=\"natjour\" /> While at Stanford, Kennedy roomed with future [[NBA]] player [[Jason Collins]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/magazine/news/20130429/jason-collins-gay-nba-player |title=Why NBA center Jason Collins is coming out now |date=April 29, 2013 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating in 2003, Kennedy joined the [[Peace Corps]]; a fluent speaker of Spanish, he worked in the [[Puerto Plata Province|Puerto Plata]] province of the [[Dominican Republic]] from 2004 to 2006, helping local tour guides in the 27 Charcos reserve in the R\u00edo Damajagua Park. He reorganized the group with some outside backing, directing the guides to rebuild parts of the park and develop skills to make the operation more attractive to tourists.<ref name=\"globe-2012\" /><ref name=\"natjour\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress-legacy/massachusetts-4th-house-district-20121101 |work=[[National Journal]] |title=Massachusetts, 4th House District |date=November 6, 2012}}</ref> \"We basically created a union,\" said Kennedy, who reported that the group's efforts won higher wages for employees while improving revenue for the tour companies.<ref name=\"capecod-2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.capecodchronicle.com/harnews/har050709_6.htm |title=Joseph P. Kennedy III Urges Young People To Act Locally, And Globally |author=Pollock, Alan |date=May 7, 2009 |work=The Cape Cod Chronicle |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624153955/http://www.capecodchronicle.com/harnews/har050709_6.htm |archivedate=June 24, 2013 |df= }}</ref> According to a press release, his other activities in the Peace Corps included \"stints as an Anti-Poverty Consultant for the Office of the President of the [[Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste]] and a Research Analyst for the [[United Nations Development Program]].\"<ref name=\"da-2011\">{{cite web |url=http://middlesexda.com/news/press-release-archive.php?reference=382 |title=Kennedy Joins Middlesex District Attorney's Office |date=August 24, 2011 |publisher=Office of the Middlesex District Attorney}}</ref>\n\n===Entry into law and politics===\n[[File:FileJoseph P. Kennedy III 2011 uncropped.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Kennedy speaking at the 50th Anniversary of the [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium]] (2011)]]\nIn April 2006, Kennedy returned to Massachusetts, where he and his brother co-chaired Ted Kennedy's [[United States Senate election in Massachusetts, 2006|re-election campaign]]. That fall, Kennedy enrolled in [[Harvard Law School]].<ref name=\"globe-2012\"/> While in school, Kennedy worked for the [[Harvard Legal Aid Bureau]], providing legal aid to low-income tenants with foreclosure cases in the wake of the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|2008 financial crisis]]. As he was a prosecutor, Kennedy worked as a technical editor for the ''Harvard Human Rights Journal'', on a staff with his classmate and future wife, Lauren Anne Birchfield.<ref name=\"globe-2012\"/> In 2007 he and Birchfield co-founded ''Picture This: Justice and Power'', an after-school program for youths in Boston's [[Jamaica Plain]] neighborhood.<ref>{{cite news|title=Joseph Kennedy III joins Middlesex DA's Office|url=http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1153512415/Joseph-Kennedy-III-joins-Middlesex-DAs-Office |deadurl=yes|accessdate=April 12, 2013|newspaper=[[The MetroWest Daily News]]|date=August 24, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130412074131/http://www.metrowestdailynews.com/news/x1153512415/Joseph-Kennedy-III-joins-Middlesex-DAs-Office|archivedate=April 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"harvard-2012\">{{cite news |url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/news/spotlight/alumni-pursuits/related/joe_kennedy_iii_election.html |title=The Next Generation |work=Alumni Pursuits |publisher=[[Harvard Law School]] |year=2012 |author=Newburger, Emily}}</ref> He began an internship at the [[Cape and Islands]] [[District Attorney]]'s Office in 2008.<ref name=\"da-2011\" />\n\nAfter receiving his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from Harvard Law School in 2009, Kennedy was hired at the Cape and Islands Office as an assistant district attorney (DA). He considered running for the Cape-based U.S. House seat held by retiring Rep. [[Bill Delahunt]] in early 2010, but decided against it.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20100301/NEWS/3010311 |title=Joseph Kennedy III says he won't seek seat |work=Cape Cod Times |author=Vosk, Stephanie |date=March 1, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115005518/http://www.capecodonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20100301%2FNEWS%2F3010311 |archivedate=January 15, 2012 |df= }}</ref> In September 2011, he joined the Middlesex County District Attorney's Office, also as an assistant DA.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://middlesexda.com/news/press-release.php?reference=382 | title = Middlesex District Attorney | publisher = Middlesexda.com |author = Jessica Venezia Pastore & Stephanie Chelf Guyotte | date= August 24, 2011 | accessdate = January 28, 2012}}</ref> He resigned several months later, in preparation for the announcement that he would seek political office.<ref name = \"Exploring_run\">{{cite news|author=Walker, Adrian |url=http://www.boston.com/2012/01/05/joek/tFAemLmqix0uZ61FajdjfM/story.html?comments=all | title = Joseph P. Kennedy III, Family Scion, Explores Run for Barney Frank's House Seat | publisher= [[Boston.com]] | date= January 5, 2012 |accessdate= February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n=== Elections ===\n==== 2012 ====\n[[File:Joe Kennedy, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|right|Official portrait of Joe Kennedy as U.S. Representative in 2012]]\n{{See also|Massachusetts's 4th congressional district election, 2012}}\nIn January 2012, Kennedy announced he would form an exploratory committee to run in the newly redrawn [[Massachusetts's 4th congressional district|4th congressional district of Massachusetts]]. Congressman [[Barney Frank]], who had previously represented the district, had announced his retirement, leaving an open field for the seat.<ref name = Exploring_run/><ref>{{cite web|author= Clift, Eleanor |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/02/17/joe-kennedy-iii-takes-the-torch-from-retiring-barney-frank.html |title=Joe Kennedy III Takes the Torch from Retiring Barney Frank |work= [[The Daily Beast]] |date= February 17, 2012 |accessdate= February 28, 2012}}</ref> Kennedy explained, \"I will then begin to reach out to the people of the Fourth District in order to hear directly from them about the challenges they are facing and their ideas on how we can restore fairness to our system. I will make a final decision about entering the race in the weeks thereafter.\"<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://www.thebostonchannel.com/politics/30140960/detail.html#ixzz1kXHYizvU |title=Joe Kennedy III Exploring Campaign Run |publisher=[[The Boston Channel]] |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate=February 28, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111162652/http://www.thebostonchannel.com/politics/30140960/detail.html#ixzz1kXHYizvU |archivedate=January 11, 2012  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author= Miga, Andrew |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/05/joe-kennedy-run-for-congress-barney-franks-seat_n_1186095.html |title=Joseph Kennedy III Takes Steps Toward A Run For Congress | work = [[The Huffington Post]] |date= January 5, 2012|accessdate= February 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Joe Kennedy III, Elizabeth Warren, Barney Frank.jpg|thumb|left|Kennedy (l\u2013r) campaigning with [[Elizabeth Warren]] and his predecessor [[Barney Frank]] in 2012]]\nKennedy officially entered the election in February 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2012/02/15/ap_source_joe_kennedy_iii_announcing_congress_bid_1329339493/ |title = Joseph Kennedy III Announcing Mass. Congress Bid |publisher=[[Boston.com]] |date = February 15, 2012 |accessdate= February 28, 2012 |first=Steve |last=LeBlanc}}</ref> In an announcement video, Kennedy declared, \"I believe this country was founded on a simple idea: that every person deserves to be treated fairly, by each other and by their government.\"<ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web | author = joekennedy2012 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b7F7MnMdtDw | title = I'm Running | publisher = [[YouTube]] |date = February 15, 2012 | accessdate = February 28, 2012}}</ref> In the same video, Kennedy vowed to fight for a \"fair job plan\", a \"better educational system\", a \"fair tax code\" and a \"fair housing policy\".<ref name=\"youtube1\"/>\n\nWhile several Democratic candidates had prepared to enter the race, the field nearly cleared once Kennedy announced his candidacy. His family roots made him the overwhelming favorite among Massachusetts Democrats.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/57_83/joseph_kennedy_iii_4th_district_clears_massachusetts-211730-1.html |title=4th District Field Clears for Joseph Kennedy III in Massachusetts  |work=Roll Call |publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly|CQ]] |date=January 24, 2012 |author=Miller, Joshua}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/editorials/2012/09/01/congressional-district-joe-kennedy-iii-for-democrats/hMDtGqN9FZ85ZoPpUVPmRK/story.html |title=2012 Primary Endorsement: 4th Congressional District: Joe Kennedy III for Democrats |date=September 2, 2012 |work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> In the September 6 primary, he faced Rachel Brown, a [[Lyndon LaRouche]] acolyte; and Herb Robinson, an engineer and musician, winning the primary with 90 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2012/09/06/bielat-kennedy-vie-for-open-house-seat-neal-keating-defeat-challengers/A7tAMApX6GgtQjtjXTAQFK/story.html |title=Bielat, Kennedy to vie for open House seat |date=September 7, 2012 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |author=Levenson, Michael}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/news/special/politics/2012/state-primary/us-house-district-4.html |title=U.S. House - 4th District - 2012 Primary Results - Massachusetts |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=September 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election campaign he faced Republican nominee [[Sean Bielat]], a technology executive and member of the [[United States Marine Corps Reserve|U.S. Marine Corps Reserve]]. Bielat had run an unsuccessful campaign against Barney Frank in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2010|2010 election]] for the 4th district seat.<ref name=\"globe-win\" /> In a series of debates, Bielat challenged Kennedy's qualifications for Congress, saying that the Democrat's campaign was coasting on name recognition rather than experience, and that he would be a [[party-line vote]]. Kennedy tried to tie Bielat to the [[The Path to Prosperity|budget platform]] of U.S. Representative [[Paul Ryan]], although Bielat responded that he only supported parts of the plan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://bostonherald.com/news_opinion/us_politics/2012/10/joe_kennedy_iii_sean_bielat_trade_jabs |title=Joe Kennedy III, Sean Bielat trade jabs |author=Stout, Matt |work=[[The Boston Herald]] |date=October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wbur.org/2012/10/16/bielat-kennedy-final-debate|title=Bielat, Kennedy Meet In Final 4th District Debate|work=[[WBUR News]] |author=Bever, Fred |date=October 16, 2012}}</ref> Kennedy raised over $4 million in support of his campaign, far exceeding Bielat's draw of around $900,000.<ref name=\"globe-win\">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/metrodesk/2012/11/06/kennedy-takes-fourth-congressional-seat-decisive-win-over-bielat/60L5XbooNio2EJbN63nmiO/story.html |title=Kennedy takes Fourth District congressional seat in decisive win over Bielat |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |author=Arsenault, Mark |date=November 9, 2012}}</ref> Kennedy won the November 6 election with 61 percent of the vote to Bielat's 36 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/election/2012/results/state/MA/house |title=Races and Results: U.S. House (Massachusetts) |work=[[CNN]] Election Center |year=2012}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014 ====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2014}}\n\nIn the 2014 election Joseph P. Kennedy III ran unopposed in the primary election and in the general election. On November 4, 2014, Kennedy was re-elected, winning a second term with 184,158 votes or 97.91%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/elections/live_results/2014/house|title=House election results|publisher=Real Clear Politics|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016 ====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2016}}\n\nIn 2016, after running unopposed in the Democratic primary, Kennedy was re-elected to a third term, defeating Republican David Rosa by a margin of more than 40 percentage points.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/massachusetts-house-district-4-kennedy-rosa|title=Massachusetts 4th District Results|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=November 16, 2016}}</ref> \nOn November 6, 2016, Kennedy was re-elected, winning a 3rd term with 265,823 votes or 70.10%\n\n==== 2018 ====\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2018}}\n\nKennedy was mentioned as a potential candidate for the [[Massachusetts gubernatorial election, 2018]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Salsberg |first=Bob |url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2016/11/28/pivoting-toward-2018-massachusetts-dems-eye-charlie-baker-challenge |title=Pivoting toward 2018, Massachusetts Dems eye Charlie Baker challenge |work=[[Boston.com]] |date=November 28, 2016 |accessdate=February 27, 2017 }}</ref> but declined, stating that he did not have plans to run for another office.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Metzger|first1=Andy|title=Kennedy says he will seek re-election in 2018|url=http://www.heraldnews.com/news/20170118/kennedy-says-he-will-seek-re-election-in-2018|website=The Herald News|accessdate=March 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\n{{U.S. Congress committee assignments\n|congress   = 115\n|ref        = <ref name=\"roll-call-bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rollcall.com/members/46526.html |title=Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy III (D-Mass) |work=Roll Call |publisher=[[Congressional Quarterly|CQ]]}}</ref>\n|committees = \n*'''[[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Energy and Commerce]]'''\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Health]]\n**[[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Oversight and Investigations]]\n}}\nKennedy was sworn into the [[113th United States Congress|113th U.S. Congress]] on January 3, 2013, and was assigned to the [[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]] and the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]. He praised the technology committee assignment as an opportunity to secure federal funding, including [[National Science Foundation]] and [[Small Business Innovation Research]] grants, for life sciences companies in his district. As a freshman in his party, he was unable to secure a seat on the [[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Education Committee]] which he had sought.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kennedy named to two House committees |url=http://www.boston.com/politicalintelligence/2013/01/04/joseph-kennedy-named-house-science-and-technology-and-foreign-affairs-committees/reYGrh482OHxYI7vKvrIAK/story.html |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |author=Jan, Tracy |date=January 5, 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:Joe Kennedy Meets With Constituent on Capital Steps.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Kennedy meets with a constituent in Washington, D.C.|Kennedy meets with a constituent in Washington, D.C.]]\nDuring a February science committee hearing, he questioned [[Texas Instruments]] president Richard Templeton regarding the company's efforts to compensate cancer-stricken former employees of its [[Attleboro, Massachusetts]], nuclear facility.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tauntongazette.com/topstories/x206923381/Kennedy-grills-Texas-Instruments-president |title=Kennedy grills Texas Instruments president |date=February 6, 2013 |author=Nichols, Christopher |work=Taunton Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thesunchronicle.com/news/local_news/kennedy-questions-ti-president-about-cancer-cases/article_9b76c27c-7096-11e2-9bc6-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Kennedy questions TI president about cancer cases |work=The Sun Chronicle |date=February 6, 2013 |author=Foster, Rick}}</ref> A prolific fundraiser, he launched his [[political action committee]], the 4MA PAC, in April.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tierney tops state delegation in first quarter fundraising |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2013/04/17/tierney-tops-massachusetts-house-delegation-first-quarter-fundraising/W7slpM42rnsE9x8yrHAgAM/story.html |author=Tracy, Jan |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=April 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/04/12/rep-joe-kennedy-iii-launches-political-action-committee/ |title=Rep. Joe Kennedy III launches political action committee |date=April 12, 2013 |author=Blake, Aaron |work=Post Politics (The Washington Post)}}</ref> As a member of the Foreign Affairs Committee, he traveled in May with four other legislators to [[Afghanistan]], where they met with President [[Hamid Karzai]] and members of the military.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kennedy impressed by US efforts to prepare Afghans |work=The Boston Globe |author=Bender, Bryan |date=May 28, 2013 |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2013/05/28/obama-and-christie-reunite-view-recovery-jersey-shore/Gp9jgxVyPm8W2O4q5ZiOWP/story.html}}</ref> That month he was named chairman of Governor [[Deval Patrick]]'s [[STEM fields|STEM]] Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mass.gov/governor/pressoffice/pressreleases/2013/0529-congressman-kennedy-to-chair-stem-council.html |date=May 29, 2013 |title=Lieutenant Governor Murray announces Congressman Kennedy to lead the governor's STEM Advisory Council |author=Massachusetts Governor's Office}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 2013, Kennedy was one of seven members of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|author=|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref> (CPC) who voted against the Amash-Conyers amendment to limit Section 215 of the [[Patriot Act]], which tried to restrict [[NSA]] surveillance programs. In contrast, a majority of both CPC members and of Democratic members of Congress voted for the amendment, while Kennedy stood out as a supporter of the party leadership. His vote has been criticized as a sign for a lack of commitment to civil liberties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/15361/why_did_83_democrats_vote_to_continue_nsa_surveillance/ |date=July 26, 2013 |title=Why Did 83 Democrats Vote to Continue NSA Surveillance? |author=[[In These Times]]}}</ref>\n\nOn January 26, 2018, House Minority Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]] and Senate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] announced he would deliver the Democratic response to President Donald Trump's 2018 State of the Union address.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-kennedy-iii-to-deliver-democratic-response-to-state-of-the-union/|title=Rep. Joe Kennedy III to deliver Democratic response to State of the Union|access-date=January 26, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Can Joe Kennedy Beat the State of the Union Curse?|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2018/01/28/kennedy-state-of-the-union-response-rebuttal-curse-216542|accessdate=January 29, 2018|work=POLITICO Magazine}}</ref> The selection of Kennedy to give the Democratic response came after criticism that the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] relied too heavily on its oldest leaders since the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]]. In choosing Kennedy, the party is trying to bridge the gap with a new face attached to [[Kennedy family|one of the most famous names in American politics]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Malone |first1=Scott |title=In step to national stage, a young Kennedy to rebut Trump address |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-usa-trump-speech-response/in-step-to-national-stage-a-young-kennedy-to-rebut-trump-address-idUKKBN1FF0G1 |accessdate=January 26, 2018 |agency=Reuters |date=January 25, 2018 |location=Boston |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126164918/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-usa-trump-speech-response/in-step-to-national-stage-a-young-kennedy-to-rebut-trump-address-idUKKBN1FF0G1 |archivedate=January 26, 2018  }}</ref> He addressed the television cameras and a live studio audience in the automotive body shop of [[Diman Regional Vocational Technical High School]] at [[Fall River, Massachusetts|Fall River]], [[Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldnews.com/news/20180130/rep-kennedy-highlights-fall-rivers-resilience-work-ethic-in-rebuttal-to-president-trump|title=Rep. Kennedy highlighted Fall River\u2019s resilience and work ethic in rebuttal to President Trump|work=Herald News, Massachusetts|date=February 1, 2018|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref> He is the second member of his family to give the Democratic response, after his great uncle [[Ted Kennedy]] replied to the [[1982 State of the Union Address]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Democrat Joe Kennedy to respond to Trump's union speech|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-42830963|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=January 27, 2018|date=January 26, 2018}}</ref> During his response to the 2018 State of the Union, he praised Black Lives Matter and spoke in Spanish with regards to [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|children who were brought into the United States illegally when they were minors]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Joseph P. Kennedy III Gives Democratic Response to State of the Union|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/30/us/joseph-kennedy-democratic-response.html}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKennedy married health policy lawyer<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalpartnership.org/about-us/staff/lauren-birchfield-kennedy.html |title=Lauren Birchfield Kennedy |publisher=Nationalpartnership.org |date= |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> Lauren Anne Birchfield (born September 21, 1984)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourfamtree.org/browse.php/Lauren-Anne-Birchfield/p457445 |title=Joseph Patrick Kennedy + Lauren Anne Birchfield - Our Family Tree |publisher=Ourfamtree.org |date=December 29, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> in [[Corona del Mar, California]], on December 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/50057691/site/todayshow/ns/today-weddings/ |title=Congressman-elect Joe Kennedy III is married|date=December 3, 2012|author=Scott Stump|work=[[MSNBC]]}}</ref> The couple met in a Harvard Law School class taught by future senator [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.wpri.com/2013/01/03/joe-kennedy-iii-met-his-wife-in-warrens-harvard-law-class/|title=Joe Kennedy III met his wife in Warren\u2019s Harvard Law class\n|date=January 3, 2012|accessdate= January 7, 2013|author=Ted Nesi|work=[[WPRI-TV]]}}</ref> On December 29, 2015, Birchfield gave birth to their daughter, Eleanor \"Ellie\" Kennedy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Katie McLeod |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2015/12/29/joe-kennedy-iii-announces-birth-daughter-twitter/TfGxiI5hWj8PawStD1p3IL/story.html |title=Joe Kennedy III announces birth of daughter on Twitter |publisher=The Boston Globe |date=December 29, 2015 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> On December 20, 2017, Kennedy announced the birth of their second child, son James Matthew Kennedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RepJoeKennedy/status/943651631698243584/|title=Meet James Matthew Kennedy. Born early this morning and doing great. First gift he received was (appropriately) a Patriots jersey from Grandpa Joe. Thanks to all for the kind words. We are exhausted, over the moon and deeply grateful!|date=December 20, 2017|accessdate= December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAn heir to [[Joseph P. Kennedy Sr.|Joe Kennedy]]'s fortune, he holds substantial investments in trusts and is estimated to be worth between $20 million and $60 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://heavy.com/news/2018/01/joe-kennedy-iii-net-worth/|title=Joe Kennedy\u2019s Net Worth: 5 Fast Facts You Need to\u00a0Know|last=Dwilson|first=Stephanie Dube|date=2018-01-30|work=Heavy.com|access-date=2018-08-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]] talk show in April 4, 2018, he stated that [[Markwayne Mullin]] was his best Republican friend.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Kennedy family#Kennedy family tree|Kennedy family tree]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://kennedy.house.gov/ Congressman Joe Kennedy] official U.S. House website\n* [http://joekennedy2012.com/ Joe Kennedy for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Massachusetts/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Joseph_P._Kennedy_III_%5BD-4%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks|fec=H2MA04073|congress=joseph-kennedy/2172}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barney Frank]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=